---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Ultra-low-mass galaxies";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Ultra-low-mass galaxies</h1>

    <p>
      Ultra-low-mass galaxies are systems with stellar masses log(M*/M☉) ≲ 7. They are expected to have shallow potential wells, bursty star formation, and be sensitive to external gas supply and feedback processes.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <h2>Example (Mukherjee et al. 2026)</h2>
    <p>
      Mukherjee et al. (2026) identify two compact components (primary–1 and companion) with log(M*/M☉) ≈ 6.34–6.91 and mass-weighted ages ≲7 Myr, undergoing recent starbursts that may be fuelled by accreting gas (arXiv:2603.11411). The inferred specific SFRs are high (sSFR ≳ 10⁻⁸ yr⁻¹) and ionisation parameters elevated, consistent with very young, intense star-formation episodes.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <p>
      Quantitatively, the MXDF companions have stellar masses in the range log(M*/M☉) ≈ 6.34–6.91 (BAGPIPES SED fits), mass-weighted ages below ≈7 Myr, and sSFRs exceeding ≈10⁻⁸ yr⁻¹. NFW halo modelling in the same work indicates the companion sits within the virial radius of the primary halo but can survive as a coherent sub-halo, illustrating how ultra-low-mass satellites can maintain isolated, bursty star formation while embedded in a larger halo environment (Mukherjee et al. 2026; Sect. 4.3; Table 2).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <h2>Why they matter</h2>
    <p>
      Studying ultra-low-mass systems informs early stages of galaxy assembly, metal enrichment, and the efficiency of star-formation feedback in small halos. In the MXDF case these components reside within a larger primary halo yet maintain distinct young populations, illustrating how small satellites can drive observable CGM signatures.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li id="ref1">Mukherjee, T., Li, Z., Zafar, T., et al. 2026, arXiv:2603.11411.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
